function longestSubsequence(nums, k) {
    const n = nums.length;
    const dp = new Map();
    let ans = 0;

    for (const num of nums) {
        let temp = 0;
        const key = [...dp.keys()].reverse().find(key => key <= num - k);
        if (key !== undefined) {
            temp = dp.get(key);
        }
        dp.set(num, Math.max(dp.get(num) || 0, temp + 1));
        ans = Math.max(ans, dp.get(num));
    }

    return ans;
}
```

    The main idea for finding the longest strictly increasing subsequence is using dynamic programming (DP). In each iteration, we iterate over the elements of the `nums` array with the given constraint that the difference between adjacent elements in the subsequence should be no more than `k`.

We use a dictionary or map to store the maximum length of subsequence that can be formed ending with each element. While iterating, we search for the largest element in the DP smaller than `num - k`. This is done using the `upper_bound` or `lowerKey` methods depending on the language.

If a valid larger element in the DP can be found, we take the length of the subsequence ending with that larger element and increment it by one (`temp = it->second` or `temp = dp.get(key)`). Then, we update the length of the subsequence ending with `num` with the maximum between the current length and `temp + 1`.

In the end, we simply return the maximum length of subsequence found.

Time complexity: O(n * log n) due to the usage of a balanced search tree (map or TreeMap)
Space complexity: O(n) for the DP map/dictionary.

